	doi          = {10.1029/2010jb007490},
	issn         = {0148-0227},
	url          = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1029/2010JB007490},
	abstract     = {We analyze 2006\#8211;2009 data from four continuous Global Positioning System (GPS) receivers located between 5 and 150 km from the glacier Jakobshavn Isbr{\^E}, West Greenland. The GPS stations were established on bedrock to determine the vertical crustal motion due to the unloading of ice from Jakobshavn Isbr{\^E}. All stations experienced uplift, but the uplift rate at Kangia North, only 5 km from the glacier front, was about 10 mm yr\#8722;1 larger than the rate at Ilulissat, located only \#8764;45 km further away. This suggests that most of the uplift is due to the unloading of the Earth's surface as Jakobshavn thins and loses mass. Our estimate of Jakobshavn's contribution to uplift rates at Kangia North and Ilulissat are 14.6 $\pm$1.7 mm yr\#8722;1 and 4.9 $\pm$1.1 mm yr\#8722;1, respectively. The observed rates are consistent with a glacier thinning model based on repeat altimeter surveys from NASA's Airborne Topographic Mapper (ATM), which shows that Jakobshavn lost mass at an average rate of 22 $\pm$2 km3 yr\#8722;1 between 2006 and 2009. At Kangia North and Ilulissat, the predicted uplift rates computed using thinning estimates from the ATM laser altimetry are 12.1 $\pm$0.9 mm yr\#8722;1 and 3.2 $\pm$0.3 mm yr\#8722;1, respectively. The observed rates are slightly larger than the predicted rates. The fact that the GPS uplift rates are much larger closer to Jakobshavn than further away, and are consistent with rates inferred using the ATM-based glacier thinning model, shows that GPS measurements of crustal motion are a potentially useful method for assessing ice-mass change models.},
	altmetric    = {true},
	date-added   = {2025-06-20 15:17:11 +0200},
	date-modified = {2025-06-20 15:17:11 +0200},
	dimensions   = {true},
	keywords     = {GPS uplift ice mass loss glaciers postglacial rebound 1240 Geodesy and Gravity Satellite geodesy results 0762 Cryosphere Mass balance 1211 Geodesy and Gravity Non-tectonic deformation 1218 Geodesy and Gravity 0720 Cryosphere Glaciers},
